			<div class="content" id="post-content-4316761">
									

<p>Ah. Well, I'm an idiot.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>So here is what happened. In the previous version of the article, I quite enjoyed the Capital R segment of the article, and since not too much appeared to change in the initial part of that section, I admit that I skimmed and missed the above details. Which is a shame, since something like this actually has precedence in Those Twisted Pines.</p>
<p>In <a href="/make-portland-weirder">Make Portland Weirder</a>, a Way to 3Ports exists in Milo Mciver State Park (which is located in Estacada, OR). This is about 10 mins further from Portland via car than Boring, so it works out that Way could exist there.</p>
<p>That said, the Ways leading from Portland, Oregon to 3Ports are so numerous that they are nearly uncountable, the only issue is that most people don't know how to activate them. So it wouldn't be that hard for WWS to acquire one of them, should they so choose.</p>
<p>On the subject of creating Ways, while I suppose someone powerful enough (ie a reality bender) could totally create a Way to 3Ports from anywhere in the world, it would be infinitely easier to do that in one of the baseline Portlands that 3Ports overlaps (UK, Maine, or Oregon).</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Anyway, I'm rambling now. Switched to an upvote.</p>

